###Tuesday, February 11

Have you ever thought abotu grass? Not the slang for weed, but the stuff Americans love to have on their front lawn.

So I've been playing this game called Equilinox, a super cute ecosystem simulation game.

You start out with a simple life form--grass. It's the first thing you plop down on a barren chunk of land to begin making the environment more welcoming for species that are pickier.

Starting with grass is a decision that makes sense given the mind-numbing ubiquity of grass on the whole entire planet.

And yet, grass is pretty recent [insert research here] okay so it's not as recent as I thought--the last thing I knew was that it was some 55 million years old. Recent research (messing around with dinosaur poops) is making it look like it might be 125 million years old.

So, okay, that means that of the three periods during which dinosaurs lived, two of them had zero grass (probs). Just... NO GRASS. Dinosaurs thundering around everywhere, and the motherfuckers didn't have fields of grass?! Also, no flowers.

What the fuck.

''Dear Diary Freewrite''

I was on the bus. An older lady got on, who began talking to the younger driver. The driver has been working for CapMetro for about a month--explains why she's still super nice and kind--and the older lady mentioned she'd been a bus driver before, too. She warned her that "they would take [her] money."

She continued talking about how employers will screw you over. Moreover, she said, people who have gone to prison and have done their time can't get a job, so they ride the bus all day, needing a place to stay in during cold, rainy days like today.

"Y'all gotta rise up," she kept saying. She mentioned that the rich keep getting richer, and the poor kept getting poorer, and if things don't change peacefully for the better, "there's going to be a war in a couple of years."

Which, I mean, I don't want to think about it--I don't know--but I //have// been fearing all of this since the 2016 election.

...Later, the lady said she used to have a nice job she was just let go from because someone kept hacking into her account and that she was told she was a liability. So... I dunnoooooo...

At some point, a woman sitting in front of me got up and loudly said, "Dios mio" as she walked to a seat further back, probably in annoyance at the lady's rant. Before, the woman had been talking on the phone about how she got beat up and her clothes had been torn, and that a group of men had saved her. I imagine she was talking to her mom--she spoke in a comfortable Spanish, with a cadence and tone of, "filling in family on my daily trials and tribulations."

<br>
I used to play this PC game called Tiles and Tribulations back when I had Windows 98. It was part of one of those "100+ Computer Games!!!" packs that were full of crapware (I loved it though).

It was a falling blocks game where you had a paddle you used to catch the tiles. It could hold five tiles max. Once on the paddle, you'd select where they could go on a 5x5 matrix. You tried to make vertical, horizontal, or diagonal same-color patterns of at least 3 tiles.

Mom really liked that game--it was very Tetris-like puzzle fare. I liked staring at the animation of the tiles flipping end-over-end.

It was published in ###1993. Ahhhhhh so old.


